# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: en-54
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] An **aspirating smoke detector** (**ASD**) is a system used in active fire protection, consisting of a central detection unit which draws air through a network of pipes to detect smoke.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] The sampling chamber is based on a nephelometer that detects the presence of smoke particles suspended in air by detecting the light scattered by them in the chamber.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASDs can typically detect smoke before it is visible to the naked eye.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] In most cases aspirating smoke detectors require a fan unit to draw in a sample of air from the protected area through its network of pipes.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] In 1970 the Australian Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation (CSIRO) used a nephelometer to carry out research into forest fires.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] Subsequently, the Australian Postmaster-General's Department engaged the CSIRO to investigate technologies that could prevent service interruption due to fire.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] After selecting a sample site to carry out research, the CSIRO suggested that the nephelometer should be used as the benchmark for the APO fire tests.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] This was installed to monitor smoke levels within the return-air ducts of the mechanical ventilation system, utilising a chart-recorder output display.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] At the conclusion of several weeks of testing, it was discovered that there no commercially available fire detection technology suitable for preventing damage to telephone equipment.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] One technology that did show great promise however was the nephelometer itself.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] In 1979, Xtralis, then IEI Pty Ltd., produced and sold an air sampling device they called VESDA (Very Early Smoke Detection Apparatus).
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] The company redesigned the detector in 1982 to provide the reliability, features, size and reduced cost for export markets.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD systems have gained popularity due to their ability to sense smoke long before a catastrophic incident.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD design corrects shortcomings of conventional smoke detectors by using a sampling pipe with multiple holes.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] The air samples are captured and filtered, removing any contaminants or dust to avoid false alarms and then processed by a centralized, highly sensitive laser detection unit.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] If smoke is detected, the systems alarm is triggered, and signals are then processed through centralized monitoring stations within a few seconds.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] Unlike passive smoke detection systems, including spot detectors, ASD systems actively draw smoke to the detector through bore holes within a piping system that runs throughout the protected area.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] Furthermore, ASD systems incorporate integrity monitoring to ensure an alert is raised at any time the ASD's ability to detect smoke is compromised.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] This is not the case with passive devices that are generally only electrically monitored with no ability to determine if smoke can actually reach the detection element.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD systems incorporate more than one level of alarm.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] This allows an ASD system to provide very early warning of an event, prompting investigation at the earliest smouldering stage of a fire when it is easily addressed.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] Other alarm levels may be configured to provide fire alarm inputs to fire systems as well as releasing suppression systems.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASD alarm sensitivities are configurable and can be programmed to levels ranging from thousands of times more sensitive than a conventional detector, to much less sensitive.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] The detectors work best in non-volatile environments.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] They can also be used in computer cabinets to alert users to the overheating of computer cables or individual computer components.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] ASDs are suitable for environments where a highly sensitive rapid smoke detection capability is required.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] This makes them suitable in clean rooms; areas which contain goods easily damaged by fire, such as tobacco, electronic rooms and highly flammable liquid and gases.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] Often, normal point detectors will recognise the danger too late, as smoke often does not reach the ceiling quickly enough for a fire to be detected in a timely fashion.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] As they can be easily hidden, pipe networks are suitable in environments where point detectors can be considered aesthetically displeasing, such as offices, apartments and hotel rooms.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] This factor also makes them suitable in locations where point detectors can be easily tampered with, such as in correctional facilities.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] Despite their high sensitivity ASDs can be used in dusty or dirty environments as long as correct design, installation and maintenance processes are followed.
[src:en-54/aspirating-smoke-detector] Most ASD products can accommodate a broad range of environments and applications – from both confined and open spaces to the cleanest or dirtiest environment, including telecomm, control rooms, waste treatment, mining and more.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The mark indicates that the product may be traded freely in any part of the European Economic Area, regardless of its country of origin.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] It consists of the CE letter pair and, if applicable, the four digit identification number of the notified body involved in the conformity assessment procedure.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The CE mark on a product indicates that the manufacturer or importer of that product affirms its compliance with the relevant EU legislation and the product may be sold anywhere in the European Economic Area (EEA).
[src:en-54/ce-marking] It is a criminal offence to affix a CE mark to a product that is not compliant or to offer such a product for sale.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] For example, most electrical products must comply with the Low Voltage Directive and the EMC Directive, among others; toys must comply with the Toy Safety Directive.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] In the case of electrical products, several later norms such as the Restriction of Hazardous Substances Directive (RoHS) and Waste Electrical and Electronic Equipment Directive (WEEE) are relevant in addition to the Low Voltage Directive and EMC Directive.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The exact significance of the CE mark therefore depends on when it was applied to a specific unit.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The marking does not indicate EEA manufacture or that the EU or another authority has approved a product as safe or conformant.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The EU requirements may include safety, health, and environmental protection.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] If stipulated in any EU product legislation, assessment by a Notified Body or manufacture according to a certified production quality system may be required.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Where relevant, the CE mark is followed by the registration number of the notified body involved in conformity assessment.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Not all products need CE marking to be traded in the EEA; only product categories subject to relevant directives or regulations are required (and allowed) to bear CE marking.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Although it has been suggested that the CE letter pair is an abbreviation of ***conformité européenne*** (as used, for example, in a written question in the European Parliament), this meaning appears to be a backronym.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] None of the defining EU Directives or EU Regulations give this association.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] When the Commission replied to the written question, they did not repeat or acknowledge those words.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] However, in a 2014 press release, the Commission gave CE as an abbreviation of *conformité européenne*.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] This is the only quasi-validation of the term that has been publicly released by a European authority.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] CE marking is mandatory for certain product groups intended for sale within the European Union, the European Free Trade Association (EFTA), and Turkey.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] As Northern Ireland (a region of the UK) remains aligned to the European Single Market under the Northern Ireland Protocol, CE marking remains mandatory for products placed on the market there, and the British UKCA mark is not required.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The formal legal status of the CE mark is set out in various EU Directives and Regulations.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The underlying principles are explained in the Commission's "Blue Guide".
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Responsibility for CE marking lies with whoever puts the product on the market in the EU, i.e. an EU-based manufacturer, the importer or distributor of a product made outside the EU, or an EU-based office of a non-EU manufacturer.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The manufacturer of a product affixes the CE marking to it but has to take certain obligatory steps before the product can bear CE marking.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The manufacturer must carry out a conformity assessment, set up a technical file, and sign a Declaration stipulated by the leading legislation for the product.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The documentation has to be made available to authorities on request.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Importers of products have to verify that the manufacturer outside the EU has undertaken the necessary steps and that the documentation is available upon request.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Importers should also make sure that contact with the manufacturer can always be established.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Distributors must be able to demonstrate to national authorities that they have acted with due care and they must have affirmation from the manufacturer or importer that the necessary measures have been taken.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] If importers or distributors market the products under their own name, they take over the manufacturer's responsibilities.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] In this case they must have sufficient information on the design and production of the product, as they will be assuming the legal responsibility when they affix the CE marking.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] A guide to the implementation of directives and regulations based on the New Approach and the Global Approach (the "Blue Guide") was first published by the European Union in 2000.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Updated versions were published on 28 February 2014 and 26 July 2016.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Depending on the level of risk of the product, the CE marking is affixed to a product by the manufacturer or authorized representative who needs to ensure that the product meets all the CE marking requirements.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] In some cases, if a product has minimal risk, it can be self-certified by a manufacturer making a declaration of conformity and affixing the CE marking to their own product.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Self-certification exists only for products that have a minimal risk for their use, and this is clearly foreseen in the relevant directive and regulation according to the product "category".
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Choose the conformity assessment procedure from the modules called out by the directive or the regulation for the product according to each category (level of risk) involved.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] There are several modules available for the Conformity Assessment Procedures, but only a few of them involve self-certification.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The most of these procedure require a "type Approval" and a Production conformity assessment by a Notified Body.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] All procedures (modules) of certification are as listed below which are derivered from Article 5.1.7 of "Blue Guide".
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The level of risk is defined by the "category" of each equipment.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The higher the category, the higher the risk.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] After defining the category, the manufacturer, in order to obtain certification, shall then apply the relevant procedures for the specific category of the product or choose the relevant procedures for a higher-category product.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The manufacturer, after insuring that the relevant modules for the product category have been applied, will affix the CE mark and draw up a Declaration of Conformity.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The Declaration of Conformity contains a description of the product, the directive(s) and regulation(s) applied, the product category for each directive or regulation, the module chosen, and the name and registration number of the notified body involved in certification procedures (models).
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Notified bodies involved in certification procedures are organizations that have been nominated by a member state (according to an accreditation procedure) and have been notified by the European Commission.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] These notified bodies act as Independent Inspection organizations and carry out the procedures as listed in the relevant Modules applied as stated by the relevant directives and regulations.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] A manufacturer can choose any notified body (notified for the certain directive or regulation and relevant Modules) in any Member State of the European Union.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The first step is to identify whether the product needs to bear CE marking or not.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Not all products are required to bear CE marking, only the products that fall within the scope of at least one of the sectoral norms (directives and regulations) requiring CE marking.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] There are more than 20 sectoral product norms requiring CE marking covering, but not limited to, products such as electrical equipment, machines, medical devices, toys, pressure equipment, PPE, wireless devices and construction products.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Identifying which norm(s) may be applicable, as there may be more than one, involves a simple exercise of reading the scope of each norm to establish which apply to the product (Such as the "Low Voltage Directive," 2014/35/EU).
[src:en-54/ce-marking] If the product does not fall within the scope of any of the sectoral norm, then the product does not need to bear CE marking (and, indeed, must not bear CE marking).
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Each norm has slightly different methods of demonstrating conformity depending on the classification of the product and its intended use.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Every Directive or Regulation has a number of 'essential requirements' that the product has to meet before being placed on the market.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The best way to demonstrate that these essential requirements have been met is by meeting the requirements of an applicable 'harmonised standard,’ which offer a presumption of conformity to the essential requirements, although the use of standards usually remains voluntary.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Harmonised standards can be identified by searching the 'Official Journal' on the European Commission's website, or by visiting the New Approach website established by the European Commission and EFTA with the European Standardisation Organisations.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The process is not always a self-declaration process, there are various 'attestation routes' to conformity depending on the Directive or Regulation and classification of the product.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Many products (such as invasive medical devices, or fire alarm and extinguisher systems, Pressure Equipment, Lifts etc.) in most cases, have a mandatory requirement for the involvement of an authorised third party e.g. a "notified body".
[src:en-54/ce-marking] When all of the requirements have been established, the conformity of the product to the essential requirements of the norm(s) needs to be assessed.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] This usually involves assessment and/or testing, and may include an evaluation of the conformity of the product to the harmonised standard(s) identified in step 2.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Technical documentation, usually referred to as the technical file, relating to the product or range of products needs to be compiled.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] This information should cover every aspect relating to conformity and is likely to include details of the design, development and manufacture of the product.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] When the manufacturer, importer or authorised representative is satisfied that their product conforms to the applicable norms, an EU declaration of conformity must be completed or, for partly completed machinery under the Machinery Directive, an ECU declaration of incorporation.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Under the General Product Safety Regulation (EU) 2023/988 (GPSR), the EU declaration of conformity is a mandatory legal document in which the manufacturer or authorised representative declares that a product complies with all applicable safety requirements.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The declaration is part of the product’s technical documentation and must be submitted to competent authorities on request.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] There are numerous 'Agreements on Mutual Recognition of Conformity Assessment' between the European Union and other countries such as the US, Japan, Canada, Australia, New Zealand and Israel.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Consequently, CE marking is now found on many products from these countries.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Japan has its own marking known as the Conformity Mark.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Switzerland and Turkey (which are not members of the EEA) also require products to bear CE marking as an affirmation of conformity.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] When the manufacturer of a machine puts the CE marking, it engages itself and guarantees, that it makes all the tests, assessments and evaluation on the product to conform to all the requirements of *all* the norms that apply to its product.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The European Commission is aware that CE markings, like other certifications marks, are misused.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] CE marking is sometimes affixed to products that do not fulfill the legal requirements and conditions, or it is affixed to products for which it is not required.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] In one case it was reported that "Chinese manufacturers were submitting well-engineered electrical products to obtain conformity testing reports, but then removing non-essential components in production to reduce costs".
[src:en-54/ce-marking] There are also cases in which the product complies with the applicable requirements, but the form, dimensions, or proportions of the mark itself are not as specified in the legislation.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] In 2008, a logo very similar to CE marking was alleged to exist and to stand for *China Export* because some Chinese manufacturers apply it to their products.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] However, the European Commission says that this is a misconception.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The matter was raised at the European Parliament in 2008.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The Commission responded that it was unaware of the existence of any "Chinese Export" mark and that, in its view, the misunderstanding had arisen because a producer had failed to respect the precise dimensions and proportions of the mark as prescribed in the legislation.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The Commission was also aware of fraudulent misuse of the mark on products that did not comply with the standards, but that this is a separate issue.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] It had initiated the procedure to register CE marking as a Community collective trademark, and was in discussion with Chinese authorities to ensure compliance with EU legislation.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Chinese (and other non-EU) manufacturers are permitted to use the CE mark provided that the goods have been manufactured in accordance with the relevant EU directives and regulations.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Nevertheless, and despite the Commission's assurance that it is without foundation, this urban myth continues to propagate on many websites.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] In March 2017, another question was put to the European Commission on the statistics of the fraudulent use of the CE mark, reasserting the "China Export" myth.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] In reply, the Commission notes that it is the responsibility of Member States to take legal action on infringements; the Commission does not have statistics on the penalties that were imposed by Member States for the improper use of the CE marking.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] In an IEEE conference paper studying the origins and evolution of the claim, the author concludes there is no evidence of a fraudulent "China Export" sign.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] In addition, similar "fraudulent" marking can be found in many European and American made products which do not show apparent noncompliance.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Typesetting C and E too near to each other is probably just a typesetting mistake.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The possibly earliest mention of "China Export" can be found on a Finnish fishing-themed discussion forum on year 2004.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The author suspects the origins start from a joke: someone has invented a funny meaning for the abbreviation CE, from which the claim has evolved as oral history and turned into a widespread myth.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Repeating the myth as a European parliamentary question has reinforced the credibility of the myth.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Directive 2014/35/EU, the "Low Voltage Directive", specifically excludes (amongst other things) *plugs and socket outlets for domestic use* which are not covered by any Union norm and therefore should not be CE marked.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Throughout the EU, as in other jurisdictions, the control of *plugs and socket outlets for domestic use* is subject to national regulations.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] It is fairly common to see domestic sockets (and adaptors) that have an inbuilt 5 volt USB-A power supply socket in addition to conventional 'two-pin + earth' AC sockets.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] These sockets must be CE marked, but the CE mark applies to the 5 volt converter *only* and not the rest of the socket or adaptor.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] This is comparable to dedicated 5 volt power supplies.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] There are mechanisms in place to ensure that the CE marking is put on products correctly.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Controlling products bearing CE marking is the responsibility of public authorities in member states, in cooperation with the European Commission.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Citizens may contact national market surveillance authorities if the misuse of the CE marking is suspected or if a product's safety is questioned.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] In the UK, sale of any product that carries a CE mark that is not so approved, or outside the scope of approval is a specific offence under Section 1 of the Trade Descriptions Act 1968.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The seller of such an article is as equally guilty as the manufacturer or importer.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Ignorance as to the true status of the sold item is no defence against a prosecution (strict liability).
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Under the Act, the misrepresentation is that the sold item conforms to a specification that it does not or that there is no such specification to which it can conform.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The procedures, measures and sanctions applying to counterfeiting of the CE marking vary according to the respective member state's national administrative and penal legislation.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] Depending on the seriousness of the crime, economic operators may be liable to a fine and, in some circumstances, imprisonment.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] However, if the product is not regarded as an imminent safety risk, the manufacturer may be given an opportunity to ensure that the product is in conformity with the applicable legislation before being forced to take the product off the market.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The mark does not have a Unicode code point.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] According to the Unicode principles, rendering the mark is a computer font design choice for the two ordinary upper-case letters, C and E, with a specific kerning arrangement.
[src:en-54/ce-marking] The exact geometry that constitutes the mark is provided in the vector graphics files available from the European Commission.
[src:en-54/cen-workshop-agreement] A **CEN Workshop Agreement** (commonly abbreviated CWA) is a reference document from the European Committee for Standardization (CEN).
[src:en-54/cen-workshop-agreement] It is, by definition, not an official standard from the member organizations.
[src:en-54/cen-workshop-agreement] In the field of electronic signatures, several CWAs exist.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] A revised version was published in December 2014; it is identical to ISO/IEC Guide 71:2014.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] In 2000 ISO and IEC published the policy statement: "Addressing the needs of older persons and people with disabilities in standardization work".
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] This policy statement recognised the need to include the requirements of older persons and persons with disabilities during the development and revision of standards.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] The policy statement also recommended using ISO/IEC Guide 71, which would become available in 2001.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] ISO/IEC Guide 71:2001: *Guidelines for standardization to address the needs of older persons and people with disabilities* was published in 2001 and has been widely accepted: it has been used in Japan and was adopted by CEN and CENELEC as CEN/CENELEC Guide 6 (see below).
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] ISO/IEC Guide 71 was also made available in Braille and was the first ISO publication that was made available in this format.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] CEN and CENELEC adopted ISO/IEC Guide 71 as CEN/CENELEC Guide 6 as a result of Mandate M/283, which the European Commission gave to the three official European standardisation bodies, CEN, CENELEC and ETSI on 24 June 1999.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] Guide 6 is part of a wider framework that standardisation organisations can use to support the need for more accessible products and services.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] The ISO/IEC Policy Statement 2000 "Addressing the Needs of Older Persons and People with Disabilities in Standardization Work" already provided principles and considerations for ensuring that the needs of older persons and persons with disabilities are addressed in the standardisation process.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] ETSI, the third European standardisation body to which Mandate M/283 was addressed, did not adopt CEN/CENELEC Guide 6 but continued using ISO/IEC Guide 71 as a reference document.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] Since 2008 ISO/IEC Guide 71 has a supporting document: ISO/TR 22411:2008: *Ergonomics data and guidelines for the application of ISO/IEC Guide 71 to products and services to address the needs of older persons and persons with disabilities*.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] In December 2014 CEN and CENELEC adopted the revised ISO/IEC Guide 71: 2014 as CEN-CENELEC Guide 6:2014.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] This new version of Guide 6 is freely available on the website of CEN and CENELEC.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] CEN/CENELEC Guide 6 is a document for participants in CEN technical bodies: Technical Committees or TCs, Working Groups or WGs, Task Forces, Workshops etcetera.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] These technical bodies are responsible for addressing the needs of persons with disabilities and older people in the standards, specifications, reports or other documents that they produce.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] 3. to raise awareness about the benefits of accessible design.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] The Guide consists of a few introductory sections followed by 10 other chapters which are called "clauses".
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] The most important chapters are described in the list below.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] Clause 7 and 8 provide tables that relate several types of clauses in a standard (for example, on packaging, the user interface and the built environment) to factors that need to be considered when addressing disabilities.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] Clause 9 provides descriptions of body functions or disabilities and their implications when using products and services.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] The last chapter is a bibliography that provides a list of resources for more specific guidance.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] In December 2001, CEN and CENELEC published CEN/CENELEC Guide 2: "CEN/CENELEC Guide 2: Consumer interests and the preparation of standards", which is a republication of CEN/CENELEC Memorandum 2 from 1977.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] This guide recommends member bodies of CEN and CENELEC to consult with consumer organisations when developing standards that are relevant to consumer interests.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] CEN/CENELEC Guide 2 is older than Guide 6 and therefore does not reference it.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] At the end of 2004, CEN adopted a "Mechanism on the use of the CEN/CENELEC Guide 6" According to ANEC it took two years to develop this mechanism and its adoption followed after "intense lobbying by ANEC".
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] When a standard is reviewed, the technical body can address the needs of older persons and persons with disabilities if necessary.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] When creating a new standard, these needs can be addressed during the standardisation work.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] When appropriate, a technical body can add a statement in the foreword of a standard that states where the needs of older persons and persons with disabilities have been addressed.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] The primary reference document that technical bodies should use when addressing the needs of older persons and persons with disabilities in their work is CEN/CENELEC Guide 6.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] CEN/CENELEC Guide 11: "Product information relevant to consumers - Guidelines for standard developers" was published in 2006 and refers to CEN/CENELEC Guide 6 for guidance on informational needs of people with disabilities and older people.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] In 2006 CEN sent a questionnaire on the use of Guide 6 to its technical committees.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] The results showed that 3 out of 275 CEN committees used the Guide 6.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] ANEC decided to propose to CEN how to take an initiative to change the situation.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] In 2007–2008, NEN - the Dutch standardisation organisation - and Standard Norge carried out a feasibility study within the European Mandate M/371.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] One of the findings was that the implementation of Guide 6 faced some difficulties.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] For this reason, NEN and CEN started an action to promote the use of Guide 6, and in December 2007 NEN proposed the installation of an CEN/CENELEC/BT/WG Accessibility for All.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] ANEC also supported the creation of such a working group.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] This led to the creation of the CEN/CENELEC/BT/WG *CEN/CENELEC Guide 6 Implementation Mechanism*.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] The working group held a preliminary meeting on 29 October 2008 and its first official meeting on 8 April 2009.
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] 2. representatives of older persons and persons with disabilities need training on the standardisation process (and CEN/CENELEC Guide 6).
[src:en-54/cenelec-guide-6] The European project USEM (User Empowerment in Standardisation) also used CEN/CENELEC Guide 6 in its training on standardisation for representatives of older persons and persons with disabilities.
[src:en-54/comite-europeen-de-normalisation] Its thirty-four national members work together to develop European Standards (ENs) in various sectors to build a European internal market for goods and services and to position Europe in the global economy.
[src:en-54/comite-europeen-de-normalisation] More than 60,000 technical experts as well as business federations, consumer and other societal interest organizations are involved in the CEN network that reaches over 460 million people.
[src:en-54/comite-europeen-de-normalisation] CEN is the officially recognized standardization representative for sectors other than electrotechnical (CENELEC) and telecommunications (ETSI).
[src:en-54/comite-europeen-de-normalisation] On 12 February 1999, the European Parliament noted in a resolution that CEN, CENELEC and ETSI co-operate smoothly and that a merger of the three standardization bodies would not have clear advantages.
[src:en-54/comite-europeen-de-normalisation] The standardization bodies of the thirty national members represent the twenty seven member states of the European Union, three countries of the European Free Trade Association (EFTA), the United Kingdom and other countries that are highly integrated into the European economy.
[src:en-54/comite-europeen-de-normalisation] An example of harmonized standards are those for materials and products used in construction and listed under the Construction Products Directive.
[src:en-54/comite-europeen-de-normalisation] The CE mark is a declaration by the manufacturer that a product complies with all relevant EU directives.
[src:en-54/comite-europeen-de-normalisation] CEN (together with CENELEC) provide a CEN/CENELEC platform for the development of European Standards and other technical specifications across a wide range of sectors, also ensuring that standards correspond with any relevant EU legislation.
[src:en-54/comite-europeen-de-normalisation] CEN (together with CENELEC) owns the Keymark, a voluntary quality mark for products and services.
[src:en-54/comite-europeen-de-normalisation] A product bearing the Keymark demonstrates conformity to European Standards.
[src:en-54/comite-europeen-de-normalisation] The Vienna Agreement was signed by CEN and the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) in 1991 but came in force in the mid-2000s.
[src:en-54/comite-europeen-de-normalisation] Its primary aim is to avoid duplication of (potentially conflicting) standards between CEN and ISO.
[src:en-54/comite-europeen-de-normalisation] In the last decade CEN has adopted a number of ISO standards which replaced the corresponding CEN standards.
[src:en-54/comite-europeen-de-normalisation] On June 9, 2022, it was announced that ASTM International and CEN have agreed to extend and expand a Technical Cooperation Agreement from 2019.
[src:en-54/comite-europeen-de-normalisation] The current affiliates are Albania, Armenia, Azerbaijan, Belarus, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Egypt, Georgia, Israel, Jordan, Lebanon, Moldova, Montenegro, Morocco, Tunisia and Ukraine.
[src:en-54/comite-europeen-de-normalisation] The current partner standardization bodies are Australia, Canada, Mongolia, and Kazakhstan.
[src:en-54/en-10027] Note that an increasing number of national European standards (DIN, AFNOR, UNE, UNI, etc.) and UK standards are being withdrawn and replaced by European Standards (EN).
[src:en-54/en-10027] This task is carried out by the Comité Européen de Normalisation (CEN) (European Committee for Standardization).
[src:en-54/en-10027] Steel specified by chemical composition.
[src:en-54/en-10027] The inclusion of a letter 'G' before the code indicates the steel is specified in the form of a casting.
[src:en-54/en-10027] Basic grade designations for category 1 steels consist of a single letter (designating application) then a number signifying the mechanical property (often yield strength) dictated in the standard for that application designation.
[src:en-54/en-10027] For some application designations another letter is included before the property value, this number is used to indicate any special requirements or conditions.
[src:en-54/en-10027] These additional letters and values depend entirely on the application of the steel and are specified in the standard and far too numerous to mention here.
[src:en-54/en-10027] The next set of 3 digits gives the steel's minimum yield strength.
[src:en-54/en-10027] So S355 has a minimum yield strength of 355 MPa for the smallest thickness range covered by the relevant standard – i.e.
[src:en-54/en-10027] Below is a table indicating the most common application codes.
[src:en-54/en-10027] In addition to the above category codes there are symbols that can be added to the grade code to identify any additional compositional requirements, delivery conditions, mechanical properties, &c.
[src:en-54/en-10027] These values depend solely on the type/application code given in the first part of the code and are so numerous as to be impossible to indicate here.
[src:en-54/en-10027] Additional symbols are separated from the main code by the plus sign (+).
[src:en-54/en-10027] The most common additional symbols are the impact and temperature codes for structural steels, category 1 - Sxxx.
[src:en-54/en-10027] In addition to the descriptive steel grade naming system indicated above, within EN 10027-2 is defined a system for creating unique steel grade numbers.
[src:en-54/en-10027] While less descriptive and intuitive than the grand names they are easier to tabulate and use in data processing applications.
[src:en-54/en-10027] The number is in the following format: x.yyzz(zz) Where x is the material type (only 1 is specified so far), yy is the steel group number (specified in EN10027-2) and zz(zz) is a sequential number designated by the certifying body, the number in brackets being unused but reserved for later use.
[src:en-54/en-10027] The current certification body is the VDEh in Düsseldorf, Germany.
[src:en-54/en-10027] Below is a table comparing steel grades from different grading systems.
[src:en-54/en-10027] The American Petroleum Institute has a standardized steel grading system for various properties of steel composites.
[src:en-54/en-10027] In order to clearly distinguish the steel grade, tubing, casing and its coupling should be painted with color codes respectively.
[src:en-54/en-10027] Color bands should be painted on tubing and casing body longer than 600mm to either end.
[src:en-54/en-10027] The whole outer-body of the coupling needs to be painted color and then color codes.
[src:en-54/en-10027] API 5B and 5CT provide various steel grades and color codes of each grade, with general information of casing and tubing.
[src:en-54/en-54] The **EN 54 Fire detection and fire alarm systems** is a series of European standards that includes product standards and application guidelines for fire detection and fire alarm systems as well as voice alarm systems.
[src:en-54/en-54] The product standards define product characteristics, test methods and performance criteria against which the effectiveness and reliability of every component of fire detection and fire alarm system can be assessed and declared.
[src:en-54/en-54] Many of the product standards of the EN 54 series are harmonised standards under the Construction Products Regulation (CPR) EU 305/2011.
[src:en-54/en-54] Annex ZA of the harmonised standards specifies which sections of the standard apply for the purposes of the CPR.
[src:en-54/en-54] This standard series is partly used around the world in several countries outside of European Union, for example in Latin American countries, Brasil, African and Asian countries and several islands in the Pacific Ocean.
[src:en-54/en-54] The standardization topics relating to fire protection were among the first dealt with by CEN.
[src:en-54/en-54] This is obvious since CEN numbers the European standards in numerical ascending order according to the date of project registration.
[src:en-54/en-54] The standard on fire classes is numbered EN 2 and the series of standards on portable fire extinguishers is numbered EN 3.
[src:en-54/en-54] The European standardization on fire detection and fire alarm systems started already in the 1970s.
[src:en-54/en-54] The EN 54 series has been prepared by Technical Committee CEN/TC72 "Fire detection and fire alarm systems" of the European Committee for Standardization (**CEN**, French: Comité Européen de Normalisation).
[src:en-54/en-54] The figure shows some examples of national mirror technical committees.
[src:en-54/en-54] The test fires TF1 to TF8 are used to test the fire sensitivity of the fire detectors according to the standard series EN 54.
[src:en-54/en-54] The combustibles selected represent a spectrum of large and small combustion particles for both grey and black smoke.
[src:en-54/en-54] These include burning liquids, plastics and cellulosic (wood) materials, and glowing and smouldering fabrics.
[src:en-54/en-54] For smoke detectors according to EN 54-7 and fire detectors with smoke sensor (parts 12, 20 and 30 of EN 54) the test fires TF2, TF3, TF4 and TF5 are used.
[src:en-54/en-54] For flame detectors according to EN 54-10, the liquid fires TF5 and TF6 are used.
[src:en-54/en-54] TF5 (n-heptane) produces a yellow sooty flame and TF6 (methylated spirits) produces a clear invisible flame.
[src:en-54/en-54] For CO fire detectors according to EN 54-26, the smoldering fires TF2 and TF3 are used.
[src:en-54/en-54] For duct smoke detectors according to EN 54-27 the test fires TF2, TF4 and TF8 are used.
[src:en-54/en-54] For multi-sensor fire detectors according to EN 54-29 and EN 54-31, the test fires TF1, TF2, TF3, TF4, TF5 and TF8 are used.
